03926nam a22006375i 9780674037724DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212010mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740377247 a10.4159/97806740377242doi  a(DE-B1597)583415  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDS109.15b.G65 2008eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a956.94/422221 aGoldhill, Simon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJerusalem :bCity of Longing /cSimon Goldhill. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 The Center of the Christian World -- t2 The Center of Jewish Jerusalem -- t3 The Center of Muslim Jerusalem -- t4 The Old City -- t5 The Oldest City -- t6 The Victorian City -- t7 The Modern City -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Jerusalem is the site of some of the most famous religious monuments in the world, from the Dome of the Rock to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre to the Western Wall of the Temple. Since the nineteenth century, the city has been a premier tourist destination, not least because of the countless religious pilgrims from the three Abrahamic faiths. But Jerusalem is more than a tourist site—it is a city where every square mile is layered with historical significance, religious intensity, and extraordinary stories. It is a city rebuilt by each ruling Empire in its own way: the Jews, the Romans, the Christians, the Muslims, and for the past sixty years, the modern Israelis. What makes Jerusalem so unique is the heady mix, in one place, of centuries of passion and scandal, kingdom-threatening wars and petty squabbles, architectural magnificence and bizarre relics, spiritual longing and political cruelty. It is a history marked by three great forces: religion, war, and monumentality. In this book, Simon Goldhill takes on this peculiar archaeology of human imagination, hope, and disaster to provide a tour through the history of this most image-filled and ideology-laden city—from the bedrock of the Old City to the towering roofs of the Holy Sepulchre. Along the way, we discover through layers of buried and exposed memories—the long history, the forgotten stories, and the lesser-known aspects of contemporary politics that continue to make Jerusalem one of the most embattled cities in the world."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArchitecturezJerusalem. 0aChristian shrineszJerusalem. 0aIslamic shrineszJerusalem. 0aJewish shrineszJerusalem. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674037724423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674037724.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK